    bio: "Mary Anning was born on May 21, 1799, in Lyme Regis, a small coastal town in Dorset, England, where the crumbling Jurassic cliffs yielded fossils like no other place on Earth. Her father, a cabinetmaker who supplemented his income by selling fossil curiosities to tourists, died when she was eleven, leaving the family in crushing poverty. From childhood, Mary scoured the dangerous, landslide-prone shoreline for specimens, developing an intuitive understanding of geology and comparative anatomy that would eventually surpass that of many university-trained men who could not bring themselves to credit her.\n\nIn 1811, at the age of just twelve, Anning and her brother Joseph discovered the first correctly identified Ichthyosaurus skeleton, a find that electrified the scientific world and challenged prevailing ideas about extinction and the age of the Earth. Over the following decades, she unearthed the first nearly complete Plesiosaurus, the first British Pterodactylus, and important specimens of fossil fish and cephalopods. Her meticulous preparation techniques and keen anatomical observations contributed directly to the emerging science of paleontology, yet the papers describing her discoveries almost invariably bore the names of gentlemen scientists who had purchased the specimens from her modest shop.\n\nAnning spent her life in financial precarity, occasionally rescued by small annuities arranged by sympathetic members of the Geological Society of London — a body that would not admit women for another century. She died of breast cancer on March 9, 1847, at the age of forty-seven, largely unrecognized by the institutions her work had transformed. In 2010, the Royal Society named her one of the ten most influential British women in the history of science, a belated acknowledgment of a remarkable life spent wresting the deep past from stone."
